<p>The concessions granted by the CCP through the ongoing negotiations were unprecedented. Seeing the Soviet Union on the verge of collapse, party officials sensed that their days were numbered, and sought to secure their interests in a post-communist China. By late 1990, the CCP's control over mainland China was crumbling, and the People's Republic of China (PRC) was on the verge of dissolution. Ethnic and regional tensions that had been suppressed for decades resurfaced, threatening the unity of the country and foreshadowing the rise of independent states across China's vast territory.</p>
<p>Section III: Reawakening the Kingdom of Tungning</p>
<p>In this tumultuous climate, the ancient House of Koxinga played a crucial role in shaping the future of China. Zheng Chouyu, a descendant of Zheng Chenggong (Koxinga), scion of the Kingdom of Tungning that ruled southwestern Taiwan in the 17th century, emerged as a charismatic and visionary leader. Chouyu returned from Taiwan to mainland China, and with significant support from the disenfranchised population, he successfully restored the Kingdom of Tungning. He was named Prince of Yangping and became the de-facto King of a revitalized China.</p>
<p>Section IV: A Dual Monarchy - The Ming Dynasty Resurrected</p>
<p>Crowds in their millions, yearning for a return to Chinese tradition and heritage, supported the re-establishment of the Ming Dynasty. Zhu Rongji, a direct descendant of the Ming imperial lineage, ascended to the Dragon Throne in Beijing as Emperor. This marked the successful realization of the Kingdom of Tungning’s original goal, and the aspirations of the Xinhai Revolution of 1912: the restoration of the Ming Dynasty. In this new dual monarchy, Zheng Chouyu maintained his positions as Prince of Yangping and de-facto King of China.</p>
<p>Section V: Breakaway Nations - The Re-emergence of Manchoukou, Mengjiang, Republic of East Turkestan, and the Kingdom of Tibet</p>
<p>The fall of the CCP and the PRC provided a unique opportunity for previously suppressed ethnicities and regions to assert their independence. The Manchu-led Empire of Manchoukou re-emerged in Manchuria under the House of Aisin Gioro as its imperial family. Meanwhile, a council of local surviving Mongolian noble families established the Mengjiang United Autonomous Government in a small part of Inner Mongolia. The long-suffering Uighur population of Xinjiang declared the establishment of the Republic of East Turkestan, while in Tibet, the Kingdom of Tibet was resurrected. Thus, the dissolution of the PRC and the CCP's rule allowed for the emergence of independent states that were no longer under Chinese occupation.</p>
<p>Section VI: Towards a New Horizon – Reimagining China in the Post-Communist Era</p>
<p>The geopolitical landscape of China, dramatically altered and decentralized, now consisted of the restored Kingdom of Tungning, the reborn Ming Dynasty, and the breakaway nations of Manchoukou, Mengjiang, Republic of East Turkestan, and the Kingdom of Tibet. As modern Chinese history entered a new epoch, the peoples of these disparate regions sought to forge a new identity that honored both their distinct heritage and their collective experience under the yoke of the Chinese Communist Party. The journey towards a more united, democratic, and culturally diverse China had just begun.</p></div>

