remely careful while navigating inside SCP-7614 projections as not to become separated from the point of entry.<br/><br/>Because of the high likelihood of filmic dislocation, preliminary tests were conducted remotely via UAVs. Human tests were conducted in heavily-controlled environments of a single long take with minimal editing. Signals broadcasted from devices within an SCP-7614 projection can be received from operators in baseline reality if the entry point is within a certain distance from the transmitter both physically and temporally. Significant cuts or chronological jumps will sever any connection with electronic devices. Contact Archives for transcripts of preliminary first and second-phase testing.&quot;</div><br/><br/>LLM response:<br/><div style="
    background-color: #fff3e6;
    border: 1px solid #ddd;
    padding: 10px;
    margin: 10px 0;
    border-radius: 5px;
    line-height: 1.6;"><p>SCP-7614 is a handheld projector that can project media onto a flat surface. When plugged into a digital device, it creates a spatial distortion that allows the viewer to physically enter the projected filmic space. Inside this space, individuals have free movement and can observe settings and figures not in the original script. There are minor deviations from reality within the filmic space, but these are not acknowledged by the characters. Scene breaks and transitions are not reported by individuals inside, and time progresses normally. However, individuals must be careful not to become separated from the entry point, as the projector can rapidly shift around and jump in time. Initial tests were done remotely and later with humans in controlled environments. Signals from devices within the projection can be received by operators outside if they are within a certain distance from the entry point.</p></div>

